eople are unable to afford adequate housing; 14m can’t afford essential household goods; and nearly half the population have some form of financial insecurity. Defining poverty as those whose lack of resources forces them to live below a publicly agreed minimum standard, this text provides unique and detailed insights into the nature and extent of poverty and social exclusion in the UK today. Written by a team of leading academics, the book reports on the extent and nature of poverty for different social groups: older and younger people; parents and children; ethnic groups; men and women; disabled people; and across regions through the recent period of austerity. It reflects on where government policies have made an impact and considers potential future developments. A companion volume Poverty and Social Exclusion in the UK Volume 2 focuses on different aspects of poverty and social exclusion identified in the study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Poverty & Homelessness.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradshaw, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDermott, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDermott, Esther, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEmerson, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFahmy, Eldin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGannon, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeslop, Pauline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlsen, Saffron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 